<keyStep pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1436,1518,2029]" box="[151,1435,1518,1539]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1518,1539]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
1. Tegmina spatula-like, wider in the apex than in the base (
<figureCitation box="[773,830,1518,1539]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1845,1867]" captionTargetBox="[176,1404,206,1816]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[164,1422,193,1823]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 4. External morphologic characters of Sphenarium and Prosphena: antennae filiform (A) or weakly ensiform (B); head subtriangular-compresed (C), subtriangular-elongated (D) or conical (E, F); tegmina spatula-like (G), strap-like (H) or tongue-like (I); subgenital plate of males tapered (J) or rounded moderately (K) or notably (L) developed posteriorly; dorsal ovipositor valves rounded (M), moderately lanceolate (N) or notably elongated (O)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/804192/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
G)............................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1436,1518,2029]" box="[151,1436,1547,1568]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1547,1568]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
- Tegmina strap-like, as wide in the apex as in the base (
<figureCitation box="[748,806,1547,1568]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1845,1867]" captionTargetBox="[176,1404,206,1816]" captionTargetId="figure@19.[164,1422,193,1823]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 4. External morphologic characters of Sphenarium and Prosphena: antennae filiform (A) or weakly ensiform (B); head subtriangular-compresed (C), subtriangular-elongated (D) or conical (E, F); tegmina spatula-like (G), strap-like (H) or tongue-like (I); subgenital plate of males tapered (J) or rounded moderately (K) or notably (L) developed posteriorly; dorsal ovipositor valves rounded (M), moderately lanceolate (N) or notably elongated (O)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/804192/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
H)................................................ 12
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1436,1518,2029]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
2. Ectophallus in posterior view without sclerotized hollow in the inner-central portion of the sheath (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[1263,1335,1576,1597]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[178,1427,201,1810]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[151,1436,193,1817]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male genital structures of S. purpurascens: morphotype 1 (A – C), morphotype 2 (D – F), morphotype 3 (G – I); and S. zapotecum sp. n. holotype (J – l). For all taxa left squares show epiphallus (I) and ectophallus (II) in dorsal view, and endophallus in lateral view (III); meddle squares show ectophallus in posterior view; and right squares show a close up of ectophallus in lateral view (Scale bars = 1 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/804204/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
B, arrow). Endophallus in lateral view with short to very long aedeagal valves and elongated pseudoarch loosely joined to the valves of cingulum (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[370,437,1633,1654]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[178,1427,201,1810]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[151,1436,193,1817]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male genital structures of S. purpurascens: morphotype 1 (A – C), morphotype 2 (D – F), morphotype 3 (G – I); and S. zapotecum sp. n. holotype (J – l). For all taxa left squares show epiphallus (I) and ectophallus (II) in dorsal view, and endophallus in lateral view (III); meddle squares show ectophallus in posterior view; and right squares show a close up of ectophallus in lateral view (Scale bars = 1 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/804204/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
A-III, arrow)....................................................................... 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1436,1518,2029]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
- Ectophallus in posterior with a conspicuous sclerotized hollow in the sheath (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[1004,1072,1662,1683]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="43.[151,250,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,200,1809]" captionTargetId="figure@43.[151,1436,193,1817]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 16. Male genital structures of S. crypticum sp. n. holotype (A – C); S. borrei (D – F); S. variabile: morphotype 1 paratype  234 (G – I) and morphotype 2 (J – l). For all taxa left squares show epiphallus (I) and ectophallus (II) in dorsal view, and endophallus in lateral view (III); meddle squares show ectophallus in posterior view; and right squares show a close up of ectophallus in lateral view (Scale bars = 1 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/804218/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
E, arrow). Endophallus in lateral view always with short aedeagal valves and short pseudoarch tightly joined to the valves of cingulum (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[1199,1266,1691,1712]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="43.[151,250,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,200,1809]" captionTargetId="figure@43.[151,1436,193,1817]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="FIGURE 16. Male genital structures of S. crypticum sp. n. holotype (A – C); S. borrei (D – F); S. variabile: morphotype 1 paratype  234 (G – I) and morphotype 2 (J – l). For all taxa left squares show epiphallus (I) and ectophallus (II) in dorsal view, and endophallus in lateral view (III); meddle squares show ectophallus in posterior view; and right squares show a close up of ectophallus in lateral view (Scale bars = 1 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/804218/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
D-III, arrow)..................................................................................................... 11
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1436,1518,2029]" box="[151,1435,1748,1769]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1748,1769]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
3. Aedeagal valves with an apical spine in lateral view of endophallus (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[925,994,1748,1769]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[178,1427,201,1810]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[151,1436,193,1817]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male genital structures of S. purpurascens: morphotype 1 (A – C), morphotype 2 (D – F), morphotype 3 (G – I); and S. zapotecum sp. n. holotype (J – l). For all taxa left squares show epiphallus (I) and ectophallus (II) in dorsal view, and endophallus in lateral view (III); meddle squares show ectophallus in posterior view; and right squares show a close up of ectophallus in lateral view (Scale bars = 1 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/804204/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
C, arrow)............................ 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1436,1518,2029]" box="[151,1435,1777,1798]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead box="[151,1435,1777,1798]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
- Aedeagal valves without apical spine in lateral view of endophallus (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[927,994,1777,1798]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[159,1427,200,1810]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[151,1436,193,1817]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 12. Male genital structures of S. tarascum sp. n. holotype (A – C); S. planum (D – F); S. macrophallicum paratype  234 (G – I); and S. minimum (J – L). For all taxa left squares show epiphallus (I) and ectophallus (II) in dorsal view, and endophallus in lateral view (III); meddle squares show ectophallus in posterior view; and right squares show a close up of ectophallus in lateral view (Scale bars = 1 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/804210/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
F, arrow)........................... 6
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1436,1518,2029]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="1563451429" country="Mexico" location="southern Altiplano" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" specimenCount="1">
<keyLead pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
4. Ectophallus in dorsal view with lateral borders of ramus strongly concave (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[994,1062,1806,1827]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[178,1427,201,1810]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[151,1436,193,1817]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male genital structures of S. purpurascens: morphotype 1 (A – C), morphotype 2 (D – F), morphotype 3 (G – I); and S. zapotecum sp. n. holotype (J – l). For all taxa left squares show epiphallus (I) and ectophallus (II) in dorsal view, and endophallus in lateral view (III); meddle squares show ectophallus in posterior view; and right squares show a close up of ectophallus in lateral view (Scale bars = 1 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/804204/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
A-II, arrow). Apical spine of aedeagus slightly longer or shorter than the base of aedeagal sclerites. Widely distributed from the 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:A12C6E25AC453B2A2CBED7C4FA3CA8E1:2C5A89E8AC453B2A2848D547FAB7A84C" box="[1121,1303,1835,1856]" country="Mexico" name="southern Altiplano" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">southern Altiplano</location>
to the Sierra Madre del Sur in central and southern 
<collectingCountry box="[593,666,1864,1885]" name="Mexico" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[679,736,1864,1885]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1094,1116]" captionTargetBox="[160,1428,201,1066]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1435,193,1073]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 7. Geographic distribution of Sphenarium species. Numbers within parenthesis in front of taxa names indicate the number of identified morphotype within the species. White surrounded areas and upper case abbreviations denote the Mexican biogeographic provinces. AC, Altos de Chiapas; AL, Altiplano Sur; BRB, Balsas River Basin; GMC, Gulf of Mexico Coast; MVB, Mexican Volcanic Belt; PC, Pacific Coast; SMOC, Sierra Madre Occidental; SMOR, Sierra Madre Oriental; SMS, Sierra Madre Sur; SO, Soconusco; and SOX, Sierra de Oaxaca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/804198/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
A).......................................... 
<taxonomicName box="[1281,1435,1864,1885]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgomorphidae" genus="Sphenarium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="purpurascens">
<emphasis box="[1281,1435,1864,1885]" italics="true" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">S. purpurascens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1436,1518,2029]" box="[151,1436,1892,1913]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1892,1913]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
- Ectophallus in dorsal view with lateral borders of ramus convergent slightly rounded (e.g. 
<figureCitation box="[1092,1158,1892,1913]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[178,1427,201,1810]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[151,1436,193,1817]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male genital structures of S. purpurascens: morphotype 1 (A – C), morphotype 2 (D – F), morphotype 3 (G – I); and S. zapotecum sp. n. holotype (J – l). For all taxa left squares show epiphallus (I) and ectophallus (II) in dorsal view, and endophallus in lateral view (III); meddle squares show ectophallus in posterior view; and right squares show a close up of ectophallus in lateral view (Scale bars = 1 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/804204/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
J-II, arrow)............. 5
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<paragraph blockId="66.[151,1436,1518,2029]" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
<keyLead pageId="66" pageNumber="67">
5. Ectophallus in posterior view with inflections of supraramus reduced or not developed laterally and valves cingulum tonguelike (
<figureCitation box="[275,347,1950,1971]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[178,1427,201,1810]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[151,1436,193,1817]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male genital structures of S. purpurascens: morphotype 1 (A – C), morphotype 2 (D – F), morphotype 3 (G – I); and S. zapotecum sp. n. holotype (J – l). For all taxa left squares show epiphallus (I) and ectophallus (II) in dorsal view, and endophallus in lateral view (III); meddle squares show ectophallus in posterior view; and right squares show a close up of ectophallus in lateral view (Scale bars = 1 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/804204/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
K). Apical spine of aedeagus as long or shorter than the base endophallic apodemes (
<figureCitation box="[1180,1250,1950,1971]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="27.[151,250,1839,1861]" captionTargetBox="[178,1427,201,1810]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[151,1436,193,1817]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 10. Male genital structures of S. purpurascens: morphotype 1 (A – C), morphotype 2 (D – F), morphotype 3 (G – I); and S. zapotecum sp. n. holotype (J – l). For all taxa left squares show epiphallus (I) and ectophallus (II) in dorsal view, and endophallus in lateral view (III); meddle squares show ectophallus in posterior view; and right squares show a close up of ectophallus in lateral view (Scale bars = 1 mm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/804204/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
J-III). Restricted to outer slope of the Sierra Madre del Sur in southern Mexico (
<figureCitation box="[803,860,1979,2000]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1094,1116]" captionTargetBox="[160,1428,201,1066]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1435,193,1073]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 7. Geographic distribution of Sphenarium species. Numbers within parenthesis in front of taxa names indicate the number of identified morphotype within the species. White surrounded areas and upper case abbreviations denote the Mexican biogeographic provinces. AC, Altos de Chiapas; AL, Altiplano Sur; BRB, Balsas River Basin; GMC, Gulf of Mexico Coast; MVB, Mexican Volcanic Belt; PC, Pacific Coast; SMOC, Sierra Madre Occidental; SMOR, Sierra Madre Oriental; SMS, Sierra Madre Sur; SO, Soconusco; and SOX, Sierra de Oaxaca." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/804198/files/figure.png" pageId="66" pageNumber="67">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
C)............................... 
